 No fewer than 18 suspected kidnappers were struck to death by a thunderstorm in Choncha forest of Toungo local government area in  Adamawa State while sharing N20m loot. The victim of the loot was allegedly said to have hired the services of marauder who uses black power to revenge his lost. DSP Suleiman Yahya, the state police public relations officer (PPRO), confirmed the happening, saying  the affected community is under Cameroon’s territory. “Yes, we heard of it, that the victims engaged the service of a local native doctor. But it was said to have occurred in neighbouring Cameroon’s territory, which is not under our jurisdiction.” The commissioner of police in the state had directed the DPO and the Area Command to engage the services of local vigilante and hunters to curb robbery and kidnapping in Toungo, Ganye, Jada, and Mayo Belwa LGAs of the state. A source from Toungo local council also said that the bandits had collected over N20m from their victims in a remote village between Koncha in Cameroon and Toungo in Nigeria. “Angered by the incessant attacks of the kidnappers, some community leaders and victims, out of frustration, consulted a native doctor to send thunder after the bandits. “They met their waterloo when they gathered to share the money,” the source confirmed. 